Happy New Year’s 
From our family to you yours. 

We have three beautiful, intelligent, and unique children, Nya, who’s in the picture with us and the other two children, Lily and Saintino who were away for New Year’s. 

I decided to add their photos to celebrate the New Year. 

If you are reading and seeing this post that means you made it through another year. 

2023 is finally here! 

Let’s take a moment to Thank God, we are all here. 🙏🏾

Going into the New Year I want you all to take this opportunity to read and share this wonderful message about “Mismanage”

Mismanagement is the most important and powerful thing life has to offer. 

Why? 

Because think about the word itself 
Mismanage! 

God the universe or whatever you may believe in gives you everything you need when you ask for it. 

But… 

If you mismanage your mind, body, and soul 
You will lose it.

If you mismanage your relationship 
You will lose it. 

If you mismanage your health 
You will lose it. 

If you mismanage where you live 
You will lose it. 

If you mismanage your vehicle 
You will lose it. 

If you mismanage your finances 
You will lose it. 

The point of the story is you can have anything you want in life but if you mismanage it you will lose it all. 

Focus on managing things better in your life and see the change that comes with it.

“Our lives begin to end the day we become silent about things that matter.” 
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. 

Today, our nation celebrates the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. We should all know that the fight for justice and equality is not a one-day event, but today would be a good start. 

Let’s encourage everyone to cultivate an attitude of service by taking today to host or volunteer for activities that improve our communities, fight against injustice, and promote racial equality for all. 

Here are Five Interesting Facts about Martin Luther King Jr. 

1.) Martin Luther King Jr. was named after Protestant reformer Martin Luther. 

2.) King entered college when he was 15 years old. 
King was arrested 29 times. 

3.) King survived an assassination attempt a decade before his death. 

4.) After his death, the King family filed a civil case against the government and won. 

5.) On August 28, 1963 - Martin Luther King Jr. gave the world his “I have Dream” Speech! 

Well, today as an African American I am proud to say: 

“I’m what my ancestors could only dream about”
- Yeshua Alexander

The true meaning of Easter varies depending on one’s cultural, religious, and personal beliefs. For Christians, Easter is a celebration of the resurrection of Jesus Christ, which is considered the most important event in Christianity. According to the Bible, Jesus was crucified on a Friday, known as Good Friday, and buried in a tomb. Three days later, on Sunday, he rose from the dead, an event known as the Resurrection.

The Resurrection is central to Christian belief because it represents Jesus’ triumph over death and sin. It is seen as a symbol of hope and new life, and is celebrated as the ultimate proof of Jesus’ divinity and the fulfillment of God’s promises to his people.

For many, Easter is also a time of renewal and new beginnings. The arrival of spring and the rebirth of nature are often seen as a metaphor for the Resurrection and the hope of new life that it represents. It is a time to reflect on the themes of forgiveness, redemption, and renewal that are central to the Christian message.

In addition, Easter is a time for families and friends to come together to celebrate with food, gifts, and various traditions such as Easter egg hunts and decorating eggs. Overall, Easter is a time to celebrate faith, hope, and new beginnings, as well as to enjoy the company of loved ones.
